<% end %>

This book is a little weird: it's written in novel format and is focused on a manufacturing plant. Don't let that throw you off thought. In The Goal, we're introduced to the [theory of constraints (TOC)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theory_of_constraints), which is an incredibly useful model for thinking about systems.

One of the concepts from TOC I refer to most often is **bottlenecks**. TOC says that a system usually has only a few constraints. These bottlenecks prevent the system from producing more - in effect they determine the throughput of the entire system. This simple concept has serious implications:

* An hour lost at a bottleneck is an hour lost for the entire system
* An hour saved at a non-bottleneck is a mirage

I find keeping these concepts in mind is super useful when prioriting features on our roadmap. After you've read the goal it's also worth checking out [The Phoenix Project](https://www.amazon.com/Phoenix-Project-DevOps-Helping-Business/dp/0988262592) . It's also a narrative-based book - this time focusing on applying the theory of constraints to software development. _Note: Don't skip straight to The Phoenix Project as it assumes you already have a solid grasp of TOC._

### [Modern Monopolies - Alex Moazed](https://www.amazon.com/Modern-Monopolies-Dominate-Century-Economy-ebook/dp/B017RC8CBC)

<% link_to "https://www.amazon.com/Modern-Monopolies-Dominate-Century-Economy-ebook/dp/B017RC8CBC", :class => 'img-link' do %>
    <%= image_tag "21-startup-books-that-changed-the-way-i-think/modern-monopolies.jpg" %>
<% end %>

Online marketplaces are sexy. Companies like eBay, Uber and Airbnb have shown how fast you can scale a marketplace. It's not surprisingly then that there are dozens of books that promise to share insights about this new business model. Unfortunately, most of them are incredibly shallow and merely end up repeating things like _"Airbnb is the the world's largest accommodation provider but owns no property"_ without actually explaining how marketplaces work.

Modern Monopolies is different. It really gets into the meat of the matter - and explains the counter-inintuitive aspects of online platforms. For instance it clearly breaks down the core functions of a platform: 

* **Audience building:** Build a liquid marketplace by attracting a critical mass of consumers and producers. 
* **Matchmaking:** Connect the right consumers with the right producers in order to facilitate transactions and interactions.
* **Providing core tools and services:** Build tools and services that support the core transaction by lowering transaction costs, removing barriers to entry, and making the platform more valuable over time through data.
* **Creating rules and standards:** Set guidelines that govern which behaviors are allowed and encouraged and which are forbidden or discouraged.

